Environmental impact analysis indicates that prolonged traffic congestion, often a symptom of insufficient public transport capacity leading to overcrowding, increases vehicle idling and fuel consumption. This contributes significantly to urban air pollution and greenhouse gas emissions, worsening air quality for residents.
Regularly measuring and transparently reporting on progress towards zero-emission transport goals is critical for accountability. Key performance indicators include electric vehicle adoption rates, public transport ridership, and quantifiable emission reductions. Data-driven insights empower policymakers to refine strategies, implement new initiatives, and ensure that ambitious targets are met efficiently and on schedule, fostering continuous improvement.
